Chronic calcifying pancreatitis revealing a primary hyperparathyroidism. The association of pancreatitis and hyperparathyroidism is rare.A 41-year-old man had consulted for a strong abdominal pain reliant to a chronic calcifying pancreatitis. A major hypercalcaemia led to a primary hyperparathyroidism diagnosis. The evolution was favourable after parathyroid adenoma surgery.The hypercalcaemia activate the transformation of trypsinogen into trypsin which is toxic for the pancreas. The role of parathyroid hormone remains unclear.